(4, 2, 7, 'Story', 'story', 'Untabbed', 'Story about Catholic', '', '<h2><strong>Our Lady of Africa statue in the Basilica in Algiers </strong></h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 0.875rem; font-weight: initial;\">In 1838, sisters from Lyon donated the image of Our Lady of Africa to the first Bishop of Algiers. It is a black Madonna an image of Mary with a dark skin </span>color<span style=\"font-size: 0.875rem; font-weight: initial;\">. The statue was consecrated in 1872 and placed in the Basilica of Our Lady of Africa of Algiers. Since then, this has been a place of pilgrimage for the small Catholic community in Algeria, and for Muslims. The inscription of the apse: \\\"Our Lady of Africa pray for us and for the Muslims\\\"is present to this day to illustrate the interreligious dimension of prayer in the basilica.</span><br></p>\r\n<h2><strong>Our Lady of the Promise</strong></h2>\r\n<p><br></p><p>In 1885 Cardinal Lavigerie wanted to disband the congregation of the Missionary Sisters of Our Lady of Africa. The sisters prayed at the statue of Our Lady of Africa to ask Mary to prevent this. They promised that if the congregation would continue, there would always be a Statue of Our Lady of Africa in the Mother House. Happily, the congregation continued and in thanksgiving the sisters placed a dark coloured statue of Mary in the garden of their mother house in Algiers. They called her \\\'Our Lady of the Promise\\\'.</p>\r\n<p>Every evening they sang the Sancta Maria around this statue. This is a hymn from the 4th century AD, very much loved by Lavigerie. When the mother house was moved from Algiers to Rome in 1964, the statue went along.</p><p><br></p>\r\n<p><strong>PRAYER TO OUR LADY OF AFRICA</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Our lady of Africa, remember all peoples especially those of Africa.</p>\r\n<p>You were present with the Apostles at the beginning of the Church,&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>be with the Apostles of today that they may proclaim the Good news of Jesus Christ.</p>\r\n<p>Help us to know and love Jesus.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Help us to follow him faithfully.</p>\r\n<p>Help us to care for one another.</p>\r\n<p>Our lady of Africa,</p>\r\n<p>may your Son choose and send new missionaries to Africa</p>\r\n<p>and the whole world</p><p><span style=\"font-size: 0.875rem; font-weight: initial;\">Amen to this</span></p>'),
(5, 2, 1, 'About us', 'about-us', 'Untabbed', 'About us', '', '<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong><strong>Missionary Sisters of Our Lady of Africa in Rwanda </strong></p>\\r\\n<p>In Rwanda, our congregation was the first women congregation to arrive on 13<sup>th</sup> March 1909 in Save. The congregation was entrusted the mission of evangelization, through&nbsp; &nbsp;teaching catechesis, establishment of schools, training teachers, setting up health centers, and training of personnel in the medical field, running social worker centers, training house girls in centers and working with women at all level. Places where the congregation of the Missionary Sisters of Our Lady of Africa extended the mission in Rwanda include: &nbsp;</p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Save</strong>:&nbsp; from 13<sup>th</sup> March 1909 &ndash; 9<sup>th</sup> August 1961.</p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Activitie</strong>s: Health Care, Catechesis, Formal School education, Promotion of women, Caring for children, and Preparation for Rwandese Religious Life.</p>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Nyundo</strong>: from 25<sup>th</sup> January 1911 to15<sup>th</sup> January 1988</p>\\r\\n<p><strong>&nbsp;Activities</strong>: Basic education, Catechesis, Health Care, visits to families, creation of hospitals and homes for people who are terminally ill, training in making crafts and household art.</p>\\r\\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Rwaza</strong>:&nbsp; From 11<sup>th</sup>October 1913to 29<sup>th</sup> August1959</p>\\r\\n<p><strong>&nbsp;Activities</strong>: Promotion of women, Catechesis, Basic education, Running Hospitals, training in making of crafts, welcoming of the needy: orphans and people abandoned by their own families.</p>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Kabgayi</strong>: From 26<sup>th</sup> October 1923 to 24<sup>th</sup> March 1985</p>\\r\\n<p><strong>&nbsp;Activities</strong>: Catechesis, basic education, alphabetization, household art, General health care and running of hospitals and maternity wards, Training in making handicrafts and domestic work, schools for health workers, training in weaving and sewing, caring for the poor and lepers, and running social schools.</p>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Zaza</strong>: From 5<sup>th</sup> November 1926 to 18<sup>th</sup> July 1990.</p>\\r\\n<p><strong>&nbsp;Activities</strong>: Catechesis, running nursery, primary and secondary schools, organizing culture and youth movements, training of catechists, establishments of health centers &nbsp;</p>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Astrida Mission / Butare parish</strong>: 29<sup>th</sup> July 1931to 6<sup>th</sup> September 1980.</p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Activities:</strong> Catechesis, Elementary education, Formal school, organizing Catholic action movements, training in household art, crafts, weaving, and serving in the chaplaincy of the military camp.</p>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Save Novitiate of Benebikira Sisters</strong>: From 5<sup>th</sup> December 1919 to December 1956.</p>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;<strong>Activities</strong>: started training and accompanying the first Rwandan religious sisters, helped in the beginning of the congregation of Benebikira Sisters</p>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Gisagara</strong>: From November 1976to 31<sup>st</sup> December 1995</p>\\r\\n<p><strong>&nbsp;Activities</strong>: Starting the training and accompaniment of the first Rwandan religious congregations, Help in the beginnings of the Abizeramariya Sisters</p>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Kinazi</strong>: From February 1980 to 13<sup>th</sup> July 1992</p>\\r\\n<p><strong>&nbsp;Activities</strong>: Training and supporting the Abizeramariya for the&nbsp;&nbsp; opening of a new&nbsp;&nbsp; community at Kinazi<strong>.</strong></p>\\r\\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Save </strong>- School for instructors: From 1938 to 15<sup>th</sup> July 1975</p>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;Strengthening the Principle of Education in Rwanda through training teachers and starting normal Schools.</p>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;<strong>Nyanza</strong>: &nbsp;From 15<sup>th</sup> January 1950 to22<sup>nd</sup> September1981</p>\\r\\n<p><strong>&nbsp;Activities</strong>: Strengthening the system of Education in Rwanda through training of teachers and starting normal Schools. Teaching household art.</p>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Astrida- Butare (clinic): From </strong>10<sup>th</sup> December 1955 to15th July 1968</p>\\r\\n<p>Activities: Running a medical hospital, maternity school, nutrition for children, and hospital care.</p>\\r\\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Butare Huye: From</strong> 7<sup>th</sup> October 1963to3<sup>rd</sup> July 1994</p>\\r\\n<p>Activities: Reformed catechism: African theological college (I. C. A.), education for teachers, youth, and lay people.</p>\\r\\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Kanombe: 29<sup>th</sup> September 1970to 11<sup>th</sup> April 1994</strong></p>\\r\\n<p>Activities: Nursing for Women and Children: Nursing at the Military Camp, Examination of Pregnant Mothers, maternity and hospital services, National Center for Family Planning (ONAPO), Care for girls and prostitutes, collaboration in parish life, catechesis, literacy campaign, caritas, caring for street children, girls\\\' education, setting up libraries, media and film making, promotion of devotions, participation in the organization activities of \\\'Religious Families in Rwanda\\\'</p>\\r\\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Kigali: 1<sup>st</sup> November 1972-to December 2015</strong></p>\\r\\n<p>Activities: Printing historical books, ; catechism, herbalism manuals; teaching theology in parishes and dioceses; accompanying families; organization of volunteers, catechism teachers\\\' associations; training primary school caregivers; attending prayer meetings; co-ordination of former students in convents; encouraging devotion to God as an important and necessary activity; accompanying children living on the street; visiting inmates; care for patients.</p>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Busogo (Ruhengeri</strong>): From 25<sup>th</sup> August 1977to8<sup>th</sup> April 1994</p>\\r\\n<p>Activities: Organising Medical and Social Welfare, National Center for Family Planning (ONAPO), Social Canters, Small Animal Husbandry, Catechism in Secondary Schools, Devotion to God, and supporting refugees in Times of War.</p>\\r\\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\\r\\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong><strong>Butare- A House of God-Preparedness: From </strong>September 1980 to September 1993</p>\\r\\n<p>Activities: Visiting the homes of the elderly, orphans&rsquo; and mentally ill; participating in parish activities: singers, billboards, preparing children for the sacraments.</p>\\r\\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Butare Parish (Reopening of Family ministry): From 12<sup>th</sup> </strong>November 1995 &ndash; To this day</p>\\r\\n<p>We are on a mission to build humanity in religious partnership with the church in Butare and the rest of the country. We are working for the development and welfare of the people through taking care of their general well-being, caring for the disabled, offering basic education to children of female prisoners, visiting homes and encouraging devotions.</p>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;</p>'),
(6, 3, 9, 'Spreading love', 'spreading-love', 'Untabbed', 'Spreading love', 'pic-ishishikariza.jpg', '<p><strong>AFRICA</strong></p>\\r\\n<p>Algeria&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Tanzania</p>\\r\\n<p>Burkina Faso&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mali&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Tunisia</p>\\r\\n<p>Burundi&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Rwanda&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Zambia&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;Ghana&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Congo&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Kenya&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp; Chad&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Uganda&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Malawi</p>\\r\\n<p>Mauritania</p>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\\r\\n<p><strong>&nbsp;EUROPE</strong></p>\\r\\n<p>Belgium&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Italy,&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Spain</p>\\r\\n<p>France&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Netherlands&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Switzerland</p>\\r\\n<p>Germany&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Poland&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp