(17, 2, 8, 'Stay in the community', 'stay-in-the-community', 'Untabbed', '', 'pic-Mother Marie Salom 1.jpg', '<h2><strong>Marie Ren&eacute;e Roudaut, SISTER MARIE SALOME (1847-1930)</strong></h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Marie Ren&eacute;e was born in Britany, France to a family of farmers. She wanted to become a religious but did not know where the Lord was calling her.&nbsp; Her cousin Yvonne told her about the hard work in the fields that the sisters were doing in Algiers, to assure their livelihood and that of the orphans of the famine, in their care. Marie- Ren&eacute;e felt that it was there that the Lord was calling her. Feeling the Lord&rsquo;s call to become a religious, she heard Cardinal Lavigerie&rsquo;s appeal to come to Algeria, where Muslim orphans were waiting for a congregation to care for them.&nbsp; She received the religious name of <strong>Sister Marie &ndash;Salom&eacute;. </strong>In 1882, during a meeting of all the sisters, she was elected the first &lsquo;&rsquo;<strong>General Superior&rsquo;&rsquo; </strong>of our congregation. She and her first sisters embodied the vison and charism of the new congregation which they have passed on to us. As a woman of faith, prayer and tenacity, she held a vital role in the young missionary congregation&rsquo;s existence. In 1894, Mother Marie Salom&eacute; sent the first sisters to Tanzania and in 1909 to Rwanda /save.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&ldquo;Be of one heart and one soul. Be truly sisters one to the other. To love and help one another are the two pillars of community life. Take with a good spirit whatever your companions do or say.\" Mother Marie-Salom&eacute;</p>'),
(18, 4, 8, 'The stages of formation', 'the-stages-of-formation', 'Untabbed', '', '', ''),
(19, 2, 1, 'Who are we?', 'who-are-we', 'Untabbed', '', '', '<p><strong>&nbsp;WHO ARE WE?</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;OUR NAME</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>We are Missionary Sisters of Our Lady of Africa (White Sisters).</li>\r\n<li>We are religious exclusively missionary sisters destined principally for Africa, but ready to respond to the needs elsewhere.</li>\r\n<li>We are Religious Missionary Sisters, founded in Africa to Serve people and the Church of Africa.</li>\r\n<li>We are sent to live in international and Intercultural Communities to share the GOOD NEWS OF JESUS CHRIST with those who do not know Him yet.</li>\r\n<li>We are women apostles dedicated to the evangelization of African Peoples.</li>\r\n<li>We are called to be All Things to all People.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>ROOTED IN CHRIST through a life of Prayer we are called to go out to those who are different.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>WOMEN APOSTLES NOTHING ELSE</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"width: 25%; float: left;\" data-filename=\"educational_tech.png\" class=\"note-float-left\">That is to say women having hearts burning with \"a strong and ardent love\" for JESUS CHRIST and belonging totally to Him. The founder Cardinal Charles Lavigerie&nbsp; &nbsp;destined these apostles for AFRICA.</p>\r\n<p>To proclaim the Good News of Christ to the African peoples: \"Tell them that this Jesus, whose cross you show them, died on it to bring all the freedoms to the world, freedom of souls against the yoke of evil, freedom of conscience against the yoke of the persecutors, freedom of the body against the yoke of slavery.\" Lavigerie (June 3, 1879)</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 0.875rem; font-weight: initial;\"><br></span></p><h4><span style=\"font-size: 0.875rem;\"><b>UNDER THE PROTECTION OF OUR LADY OF AFRICA</b></span></h4><h4><span style=\"font-size: 0.875rem;\"><b><br></b></span></h4>\r\n<p>We are under the protection of Our Lady of Africa. Because for us Mary is the one who believed and collaborated in the Redemption. As in the time of the apostles, she is present wherever the church is being built.</p>\r\n<p>In 1885 Cardinal Lavigerie wanted to disband our congregation. The sisters went to pray at the statue of Our Lady of Africa to ask Mary to prevent this. They promised that if the congregation would continue, there would always be a Statue of Our Lady of Africa in the Mother House. Happily, the congregation continued and in thanksgiving the sisters placed a dark coloured statue of Mary in the garden of their mother house in Algiers. They called her Our Lady of the promise. Every evening they sang the Sancta Maria around this statue. When the mother house was moved from Algiers to Rome in 1964, the statue was carried along.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>WE ARE CALLED WHITE SISTERS</p>\r\n<p>It is because of the long white habit that our sisters used to wear that people gave us the name White Sisters.</p>'),
(20, 11, 4, 'What is Vocation?', 'what-is-vocation', 'Untabbed', 'What is Vacation?', 'pic-face6.jpg', '<p>Vacation is&nbsp;<span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: &quot;Open Sans&quot;, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; text-align: justify; font-weight: initial;\">He was born in Bayonne, France in 1825. Already before his ordination in 1849, he was interested in the missionary life.</span></p><p style=\"margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 15px; margin-left: 0px; padding: 0px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: &quot;Open Sans&quot;, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; text-align: justify;\"><font style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: inherit;\"><font style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: inherit;\">In 1863 he was nominated Bishop of Nancy, France.&nbsp;</font><font style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: inherit;\">As the youngest bishop of France, he took office in Algeria in 1866.&nbsp;</font><font style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: inherit;\">Thus, he resigned from the proposal to accept the title of Primate of France.&nbsp;</font><font style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: inherit;\">In a few words, he outlined the purpose of his new task:</font></font></p><p style=\"margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 15px; margin-left: 0px; padding: 0px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: &quot;Open Sans&quot;, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; text-align: justify;\"><font style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: inherit;\"><font style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: inherit;\">Algeria is a gate opened by Providence to a continent of two hundred million souls.&nbsp;</font><font style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: inherit;\">And it is here, above all, that the Catholic apostolate must be fulfilled. \"</font></font></p><p style=\"margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 15px; margin-left: 0px; padding: 0px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: &quot;Open Sans&quot;, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; text-align: justify;\"><font style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: inherit;\"><font style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: inherit;\">Lavigerie, the shepherd of the Algerian community, was a man very open, not only to the needs of Christians, but also very much to the needs of this country, colonized by his countrymen.&nbsp;</font><font style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: inherit;\">After assuming the bishopric of Algiers, he established two congregations: the African Missionary Sisters in 1869 (the so-called White Sisters) and the African Missionaries.</font></font></p>'),
(21, 11, 4, 'Missionary Vocation', 'missionary-vocation', 'Untabbed', 'What is Missionary Vocation?', '', '<p style=\"margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 15px; margin-left: 0px; padding: 0px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: \"Open Sans\", sans-serif; font-size: 16px; text-align: justify;\"><font style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: inherit;\">Vacation He was born in Bayonne, France in 1825. Already before his ordination in 1849, he was interested in the missionary life.</font></p><p style=\"margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 15px; margin-left: 0px; padding: 0px; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: \"Open Sans\", sans-serif; font-size: 16px; text-align: justify;\"><font style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: inherit;\"><font style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: inherit;\">In 1863 he was nominated Bishop of Nancy, France.</font><font style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: inherit;\">As the youngest bishop of France, he took office in Algeria in 1866.</font><font style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: inherit;\">Thus, he resigned from the proposal to accept the title of Primate of France.</font><font style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: inherit;\">In a few words, he outlined the purpose of his new task</font></font></p>'),
